WEBVTT

00:03.253 --> 00:07.006
PlCARD:
Captain's log, stardate 42609.1 .

00:07.215 --> 00:10.259
ln response to a desperate plea
from my old friend,

00:10.468 --> 00:13.012
Captain Donald Varley
ofthe U.S.S. Yamato,

00:13.221 --> 00:15.973
l'm running a grave risk
by taking the Enterprise

00:16.182 --> 00:17.975
into the Neutral Zone.

00:18.184 --> 00:20.853
Varley's request was prompted
by dangerous malfunctions

00:21.062 --> 00:22.688
which have been plaguing
our sister ship.

00:23.064 --> 00:24.940
Perhaps with both crews
working together,

00:25.150 --> 00:26.734
we can eliminate the problems

00:26.943 --> 00:30.446
before our presence is detected
by the Romulans.

00:33.867 --> 00:36.326
How long to rendezvous,
Mr. Crusher?

00:36.536 --> 00:39.329
Four minutes and 33 seconds, sir.

00:39.539 --> 00:41.290
Status of download, Mr. Data?

00:41.499 --> 00:44.043
The Yamato log should be
in our computer by rendezvous, sir.

00:44.252 --> 00:46.545
Have you nailed down
our little hiccup yet?

00:46.755 --> 00:48.297
- Sir?
- The odd reading?

00:48.506 --> 00:50.382
No, sir. lt might be due to problems

00:50.592 --> 00:53.427
currently being experienced
by the Yamato.

00:55.055 --> 00:56.472
Trouble, Number One?

00:56.973 --> 00:59.391
l'm not sure, sir.
Are we alone out here, Worf?

00:59.601 --> 01:03.187
Yes, sir. There are no other vessels
in the area except the Yamato,

01:03.396 --> 01:06.440
which is coming
into visual range now.

01:06.649 --> 01:08.233
At last.

01:10.111 --> 01:11.904
WORF:
Transmission from the Yamato, sir.

01:12.072 --> 01:13.781
PlCARD:
On viewer.

01:15.033 --> 01:16.658
Donald.

01:17.619 --> 01:20.537
What's a nice Starfleet captain like you
doing in a place like this?

01:20.955 --> 01:22.873
It's good to see you again,
Jean-Luc,

01:23.083 --> 01:25.334
despite your antique humor.

01:25.543 --> 01:28.295
I only hope your people
are able to help us.

01:28.505 --> 01:31.882
Malfunctions are becoming serious.

01:32.509 --> 01:34.718
We lost an Engineering team.

01:34.928 --> 01:38.847
The computer shut down a force field
in an open shuttle bay.

01:39.724 --> 01:41.767
Eighteen people.

01:43.895 --> 01:45.646
Do you have any idea
what caused this, sir?

01:45.855 --> 01:48.774
None. They're affecting every system
simultaneously.

01:48.983 --> 01:51.860
It's like the ship suddenly decided
to fall apart.

01:52.070 --> 01:55.114
lt's beginning to make me think that
we should've run Galaxy-class ships

01:55.323 --> 01:58.158
across a few more drawing boards
before we built one.

01:58.493 --> 02:00.452
You believe it's a design flaw?

02:00.662 --> 02:03.956
l don't know.
l'm grasping at straws here.

02:04.165 --> 02:05.707
All l know is we've got to get it fixed

02:05.917 --> 02:08.544
and before l lose more
than an Engineering team.

02:08.920 --> 02:09.962
Do you wish to evacuate

02:10.171 --> 02:12.631
any non-essential personnel
to the Enterprise, sir?

02:12.841 --> 02:16.009
No. No, that would be premature.

02:16.386 --> 02:19.304
Donald, we'll get our teams
to work on it immediately.

02:19.514 --> 02:21.473
l'm sure neither of us
feels too comfortable

02:21.683 --> 02:23.308
sitting around in the Neutral Zone.

02:23.726 --> 02:27.229
I know what you're thinking.
What the hell am l doing here?

02:27.438 --> 02:33.318
Well, l heard rumors
about a couple of archaeological digs

02:33.528 --> 02:37.072
that started making the lconians
sound a lot less like legend.

02:37.407 --> 02:41.118
l did a little investigating
and l located their home-world.

02:41.327 --> 02:42.870
ln the Neutral Zone?

02:43.079 --> 02:44.788
ln the Neutral Zone.

02:45.290 --> 02:50.169
Donald, that was quite a risk to run
to satisfy archaeological curiosity.

02:50.587 --> 02:54.756
The risk would be in allowing
the Romulans to locate lconia.

02:57.760 --> 03:00.429
Fortunately, l got there first.

03:01.097 --> 03:03.056
It's a virtually dead planet.

03:03.266 --> 03:05.517
Enough technology remains

03:05.727 --> 03:09.479
to give the Romulans an edge,
if they should find it.

03:10.899 --> 03:13.275
Donald,
your transmission is breaking up.

03:13.484 --> 03:15.277
Mr. Data, try and clean that up.

03:15.445 --> 03:16.695
[PANEL BEEPlNG]

03:16.863 --> 03:20.616
Sir, there is an energy buildup
in the Yamato's Engineering section.

03:22.327 --> 03:24.912
Yamato, this is the Enterprise.

03:25.246 --> 03:27.414
Yamato, come in.

03:27.916 --> 03:31.543
Captain, magnetic seals in the
antimatter chamber are decaying.

03:31.753 --> 03:33.253
Captain.

03:33.630 --> 03:35.714
Donald, come in!

03:39.135 --> 03:40.677
Shields up.

03:40.845 --> 03:42.930
[RED ALERT SOUNDlNG]

03:46.100 --> 03:47.726
Sir...

03:50.563 --> 03:54.691
Sensors indicate
no life readings, sir.

04:00.907 --> 04:01.949
WORF:
Captain.

04:02.325 --> 04:05.744
Another vessel is coming
within sensor range.

04:06.079 --> 04:07.621
lt is Romulan.

04:30.853 --> 04:34.982
PlCARD:
Space, the final frontier.

04:35.692 --> 04:39.611
These are the voyages
ofthe starship Enterprise.

04:39.821 --> 04:45.033
lts continuing mission:
to explore strange new worlds,

04:45.618 --> 04:49.746
to seek out new life
and new civilizations,

04:50.206 --> 04:54.626
to boldly go where no one
has gone before.

05:50.516 --> 05:52.434
PlCARD:
Captain's log, supplemental.

05:52.602 --> 05:55.395
The Yamato's entire crew
and their families,

05:55.605 --> 05:58.231
more than a thousand people,
have been lost.

05:58.441 --> 06:03.195
Circumstances unfortunately
permit us no pause for grief.

06:03.946 --> 06:06.073
No response
from the Romulan vessel.

06:06.282 --> 06:09.076
Arm phasers
and prepare to lock on target.

06:09.285 --> 06:11.244
Did they attack the Yamato?

06:11.788 --> 06:13.580
Unknown, sir.

06:13.956 --> 06:16.500
WORF: All their weapon systems
have been fully activated.

06:16.709 --> 06:18.794
Still no response.

06:19.545 --> 06:20.921
Romulan vessel,

06:21.130 --> 06:24.841
this is Captain Jean-Luc Picard
of the U.S.S. Enterprise.

06:27.512 --> 06:28.929
TARlS:
Captain Picard.

06:30.890 --> 06:33.850
Explain your illegal presence
in the Neutral Zone.

06:34.060 --> 06:36.269
Explain yours.

06:36.646 --> 06:39.523
Are you responsible
for the destruction of the Yamato?

06:40.024 --> 06:43.193
No. But believe me, captain,

06:43.403 --> 06:46.988
had we chosen to exercise our right
to defend the Neutral Zone,

06:47.198 --> 06:50.242
we would not have stopped
with one starship.

06:50.451 --> 06:53.161
You will leave at once.

06:57.083 --> 06:58.875
WORF: Mute.
- Comments?

06:59.085 --> 07:00.419
She's extremely anxious.

07:00.628 --> 07:03.422
Understandable if she just destroyed
a Federation starship.

07:03.631 --> 07:05.090
Your scan was inconclusive.

07:05.299 --> 07:07.050
We don't know what happened
to the Yamato.

07:07.385 --> 07:09.553
Our presence in the Neutral Zone
is provocative.

07:09.762 --> 07:12.305
lt could force her to respond.

07:17.895 --> 07:19.187
Open.

07:19.397 --> 07:21.648
We will comply

07:21.858 --> 07:25.068
when l have determined the cause
of the destruction of the Yamato,

07:25.278 --> 07:28.864
and when l am fully satisfied that you
were not responsible. Picard out.

07:32.243 --> 07:33.952
They're engaging
their cloaking device.

07:34.162 --> 07:36.663
Good.
They can't fire when they're cloaked.

07:36.873 --> 07:39.749
Unless they have overcome
that deficiency.

07:39.959 --> 07:42.544
The Yamato was destroyed
while they were cloaked.

07:42.753 --> 07:45.881
Enough. Answers.
l want answers, not conjecture.

07:46.090 --> 07:48.758
Number One, l want them
at a staff meeting in one hour.

07:48.968 --> 07:50.427
RlKER:
Aye, sir.

07:55.266 --> 07:57.601
Sensor recordings reveal
that what we witnessed

07:57.810 --> 08:02.355
was an uncontrolled and catastrophic
matter-antimatter mix.

08:02.565 --> 08:05.609
The magnetic seals between
the chambers collapsed and--

08:05.818 --> 08:07.360
PlCARD:
Wait, wait.

08:07.945 --> 08:09.446
That's not possible.

08:09.655 --> 08:10.739
Yes, sir, it is,

08:10.948 --> 08:12.782
but a highly improbable
set of circumstances

08:12.992 --> 08:15.535
has to take place
for such a result to occur.

08:16.204 --> 08:17.621
Explain.

08:18.247 --> 08:21.374
Okay. ln the event
of a breach of seal integrity,

08:21.584 --> 08:25.420
there's an emergency release system
which dumps the antimatter.

08:25.630 --> 08:28.548
Apparently such a dump began,
was then halted,

08:28.758 --> 08:30.550
and the containment seals
were dropped.

08:30.760 --> 08:34.596
There was still sufficient antimatter
present to lead to an explosion.

08:34.805 --> 08:37.557
And so there is no evidence
that a weapon was used?

08:38.059 --> 08:39.643
No, sir. None.

08:39.852 --> 08:42.854
However it happened,
the Yamato did it to herself.

08:43.314 --> 08:45.106
Theorize.

08:45.525 --> 08:49.027
What could have caused
such a catastrophic malfunction?

08:49.445 --> 08:51.988
Well, l think Captain Varley
may have been right.

08:52.198 --> 08:54.282
There may be a design flaw.

08:54.492 --> 08:57.327
- ln a Galaxy-class starship?
LA FORGE: Yes, sir.

08:57.537 --> 09:00.288
lt's the most sophisticated
piece of machinery ever built.

09:00.498 --> 09:02.207
Something
could have been overlooked.

09:02.833 --> 09:04.459
Knowing where the flaw is located,

09:04.669 --> 09:07.337
can you isolate the problem
and solve it?

09:07.547 --> 09:09.673
We're already working on it, sir.

09:10.132 --> 09:11.800
Pull any personnel you can use.

09:15.596 --> 09:18.014
lf we have established
that the Romulans

09:18.224 --> 09:20.725
were not responsible
for the destruction of the Yamato,

09:21.394 --> 09:23.645
would it not be prudent to withdraw?

09:25.481 --> 09:28.316
lf it is a design flaw,
we're better to stay where we are

09:28.526 --> 09:30.986
and give Geordi time to work on it.

09:31.445 --> 09:35.323
Or what happened to the Yamato
could happen to us.

09:51.007 --> 09:56.595
Computer, access
Captain Donald Varley's personal log.

09:56.971 --> 09:59.264
Search parameter,

09:59.640 --> 10:06.187
locate entries containing words
Romulan and/or lconia.

10:06.397 --> 10:07.897
COMPUTER:
Working.

10:09.692 --> 10:11.443
Personal log.

10:11.652 --> 10:14.237
lt was kind of Dr. Ramsey
to allow me

10:14.447 --> 10:16.823
to carry away
my own little piece of legend

10:17.033 --> 10:20.035
from the archaeological dig
at Denius lll.

10:20.244 --> 10:22.954
My engineers have examined it,

10:23.205 --> 10:27.000
but are completely baffled
by its technology.

10:28.586 --> 10:30.503
What was its purpose?

10:31.088 --> 10:34.549
l'm like a caveman
confronted by a tricorder.

10:34.759 --> 10:38.303
l'm certain this device is lconian.
But how far had it traveled

10:38.512 --> 10:42.682
before it was abandoned
on this alien world?

10:44.727 --> 10:46.936
Personal log.

10:47.229 --> 10:49.564
A galactic Rosetta stone.

10:49.982 --> 10:53.151
The starfields on the artifact
were unintelligible

10:53.361 --> 10:57.781
until l took into account
200 millennia of stellar drift.

10:57.990 --> 11:01.076
After that,
it was easy to pinpoint lconia.

11:03.120 --> 11:05.205
My first officer
is questioning the wisdom

11:05.414 --> 11:08.041
of my order
to violate the Neutral Zone,

11:08.626 --> 11:12.379
but l'm convinced
that l've taken the only proper course.

11:12.588 --> 11:15.799
Should this advanced technology
fall into the hands of the Romulans,

11:16.008 --> 11:18.259
we might as well dock our ships

11:18.469 --> 11:21.137
and defend ourselves with sticks.

11:22.473 --> 11:23.973
Personal log.

11:24.183 --> 11:26.059
We've been spotted
by a Romulan cruiser,

11:26.268 --> 11:30.021
but after playing hide-and-seek
through several solar systems,

11:30.231 --> 11:32.691
l think l've managed to elude them.

11:34.193 --> 11:36.986
The lconian probe scan.

11:37.530 --> 11:40.073
Was it
an attempted communication?

11:40.616 --> 11:44.786
lf only l knew
what we were dealing with here.

11:46.247 --> 11:48.206
Personal log.

11:48.416 --> 11:51.334
I'm unable to send an away team
to the surface of lconia,

11:51.544 --> 11:53.670
nor can I scan the energy source
of the planet

11:53.879 --> 11:57.215
because of these maddening
systems failures.

11:57.466 --> 11:58.925
lt's infuriating to be stopped

11:59.135 --> 12:02.178
at the threshold of a dream
by one's own ship.

12:02.805 --> 12:05.724
We're leaving orbit
to rendezvous with Picard.

12:05.933 --> 12:08.643
lf his people can't help us
repair theYamato,

12:08.853 --> 12:13.440
l must convince him
to continue this exploration.

12:13.649 --> 12:16.025
The future well being
of the Federation

12:16.235 --> 12:18.486
may well depend upon it.

12:19.447 --> 12:23.575
COMPUTER: No further entries
conforming to search parameters.

12:33.419 --> 12:35.086
[DOOR BUZZES]

12:51.812 --> 12:56.649
Mr. Data, there was a reference
in Captain Varley's personal log

12:56.859 --> 12:58.943
to a probe that scanned the Yamato.

12:59.153 --> 13:01.738
Aye, sir, we have a visual record.

13:02.740 --> 13:04.783
Put it on main viewer.

13:07.286 --> 13:09.370
What the devil is that?

13:15.753 --> 13:17.754
Have you seen anything
like that before?

13:17.963 --> 13:21.841
No, sir. lt appears to be a scanner,
possibly a transmitter.

13:22.051 --> 13:23.593
Transmitting what?

13:23.803 --> 13:25.094
Unknown, sir.

13:25.763 --> 13:28.139
- Engineering.
- La Forge.

13:28.349 --> 13:31.059
PlCARD: What progress
on the matter-antimatter scan?

13:31.268 --> 13:32.602
Everything continues to check out.

13:32.812 --> 13:35.480
l'm starting an analysis
on the magnetic coils.

13:36.023 --> 13:38.233
When the Yamato was probed,
where was she?

13:38.442 --> 13:43.571
ln orbit around a planet,
at coordinates 227, mark 359, sir.

13:46.992 --> 13:49.160
ETA at warp factor 8?

13:49.370 --> 13:51.704
DATA:
Twelve hours, 16 minutes, sir.

13:51.914 --> 13:54.499
Sir, that would put us
substantially close

13:54.708 --> 13:56.876
to the Romulan side
of the Neutral Zone.

13:57.086 --> 13:59.128
That can't be helped.
Ensign, lay in a course.

13:59.338 --> 14:01.256
- Warp factor 8.
- Aye, sir.

14:01.799 --> 14:04.008
We're going to assume
the Yamato's mission.

14:04.218 --> 14:05.635
And risk a war?

14:06.136 --> 14:09.639
Perhaps prevent one.

14:16.564 --> 14:17.605
[DOOR CHlMES]

14:17.773 --> 14:18.982
Come.

14:22.236 --> 14:25.071
Sir?
May l speak with you a moment?

14:27.199 --> 14:29.033
Yes, of course.

14:34.957 --> 14:36.499
Well, what is it, Wesley?

14:37.710 --> 14:40.211
lt's about the lconians, sir.

14:40.588 --> 14:42.630
l was told they were just a myth.

14:42.840 --> 14:47.010
China was thought to be a myth
until Marco Polo traveled there.

14:47.219 --> 14:49.220
No, the lconians were certainly real.

14:49.430 --> 14:51.014
Sit down.

14:51.223 --> 14:54.726
We know that three systems
within this sector

14:54.935 --> 14:56.644
had a number of cultural similarities,

14:56.854 --> 14:58.646
similarities
which could only be explained

14:58.856 --> 15:01.441
by there being
a single, unifying influence.

15:01.650 --> 15:03.401
So they colonized those worlds?

15:04.111 --> 15:05.486
Probably conquered.

15:05.696 --> 15:07.947
You mean they were warlike?

15:08.198 --> 15:09.657
Perhaps.

15:09.867 --> 15:16.039
Ancient text did speak
of demons of air and darkness.

15:16.248 --> 15:17.957
Air and darkness?

15:18.167 --> 15:22.670
Legend has it that they traveled
without the benefit of spaceships,

15:22.880 --> 15:27.216
merely appearing out of thin air
on distant planets.

15:27.426 --> 15:29.093
Sounds like magic.

15:29.303 --> 15:33.640
Well, we would appear magical
to Stone Age people.

15:35.309 --> 15:37.226
How did you find all this out?

15:38.312 --> 15:41.689
Archeology has been a hobby of mine
since Academy days.

15:41.899 --> 15:46.945
But why don't we talk about
what really brought you here?

15:51.909 --> 15:54.243
lt's the Yamato, captain.

15:55.120 --> 15:57.413
l can't stop thinking about her.

15:59.333 --> 16:04.128
All those people...dead.

16:05.005 --> 16:09.008
l don't know how you
and Commander Riker and Geordi,

16:09.218 --> 16:11.844
how you handle it so easily.

16:12.179 --> 16:13.805
Easily?

16:15.307 --> 16:17.684
Oh, no, not easily.

16:20.104 --> 16:22.021
We handle it
because we're trained to.

16:23.273 --> 16:24.732
As you will be.

16:24.942 --> 16:26.651
Tea, Earl Grey, hot.

16:27.277 --> 16:29.904
But if ever the time comes

16:30.114 --> 16:33.700
when the death of a single individual
fails to move us...

16:33.867 --> 16:35.368
[REPLlCATOR BUZZlNG]

16:44.086 --> 16:45.670
Didn't you order tea, sir?

16:46.005 --> 16:48.381
Now, that should not
have happened.

16:49.425 --> 16:50.800
PlCARD:
Captain's log, supplemental.

16:50.968 --> 16:52.301
As happened with our sister ship,

16:52.511 --> 16:54.095
the Enterprise is beginning
to experience

16:54.304 --> 16:55.972
a series of system failures.

16:56.181 --> 16:58.016
So far they are random,

16:58.225 --> 16:59.767
but l fear
they could be early symptoms

16:59.977 --> 17:01.811
of what happened to theYamato.

17:02.021 --> 17:04.897
PlCARD [OVER COM]: Engineering.
- La Forge.

17:05.107 --> 17:06.858
Lieutenant,
are you making any progress

17:07.067 --> 17:08.359
towards solving our problems?

17:08.569 --> 17:11.446
LA FORGE: Solving them, no, sir,
but l can eliminate one worry.

17:11.655 --> 17:13.656
lt is not a design flaw.

17:13.866 --> 17:15.324
l've been reviewing the Yamato's log

17:15.534 --> 17:18.745
and l think that alien probe may have
something to do with their problems.

17:18.954 --> 17:21.581
PlCARD: How?
- l'd need to see the thing.

17:21.915 --> 17:25.752
lf it was the probe,
that explains the Yamato.

17:25.961 --> 17:29.380
How do you account for the difficulties
the Enterprise is experiencing?

17:29.798 --> 17:31.007
l can't.

17:31.216 --> 17:33.968
PlCARD: Lieutenant,
are our problems likely to attain

17:34.178 --> 17:36.804
the seriousness
ofthose on the Yamato?

17:37.014 --> 17:39.599
lf you're asking for speculation,
l'd say, yes, sir, they are.

17:39.808 --> 17:41.309
l need time.

17:42.352 --> 17:47.231
Mr. La Forge, time is one thing
we do not have in abundance.

18:00.496 --> 18:04.082
PlCARD: Analysis, Mr. Data.
DATA: Scanning, sir.

18:10.464 --> 18:12.048
Well, Mr. Data?

18:12.257 --> 18:14.133
No life form readings, sir.

18:14.343 --> 18:16.344
All major cities
have been heavily damaged,

18:16.553 --> 18:17.762
and the pattern of destruction

18:17.971 --> 18:21.349
is that consistent
with large-scale, orbital bombardment.

18:22.267 --> 18:26.604
- How long ago?
- Approximately 200,000 years, sir.

18:27.356 --> 18:28.856
There is an energy source

18:29.066 --> 18:31.275
in the mountains
of the smaller continent.

18:31.485 --> 18:33.277
PlCARD:
Magnify.

18:35.864 --> 18:37.782
ls that lconia?

18:38.075 --> 18:40.868
Captain Varley died
believing that it was.

18:43.372 --> 18:44.413
RlKER:
Did you see that?

18:44.581 --> 18:45.623
[PANEL BEEPlNG]

18:45.791 --> 18:48.126
Captain, projectile launched
from the planet's surface.

18:48.836 --> 18:50.002
lts size and composition

18:50.212 --> 18:53.214
match the probe
which scanned the Yamato, sir.

18:53.799 --> 18:56.008
Shields up. Prepare a tractor beam.

18:56.218 --> 19:00.513
Mr. La Forge, l'm going to assist you
in your research.

19:00.722 --> 19:03.057
A probe has been launched
from lconia.

19:03.767 --> 19:06.018
l'm going to capture it.

19:07.312 --> 19:08.771
No, sir, wait!

19:08.981 --> 19:11.732
Captain! Captain!

19:15.320 --> 19:17.196
[DOOR BUZZlNG]

19:21.410 --> 19:23.077
Coming through!

19:26.123 --> 19:27.790
Bridge!

19:29.334 --> 19:31.627
[TURBOLlFT WHlRRlNG
lNTENSELY]

19:32.588 --> 19:35.047
Emergency stop!

19:35.591 --> 19:37.341
[YELLS]

19:42.139 --> 19:45.057
Stop it! Damn it!

19:45.225 --> 19:47.268
[GRUNTS]

19:55.569 --> 19:56.611
[YELLS]

20:07.122 --> 20:09.040
Tractor beam ready, sir.

20:09.208 --> 20:10.875
[LA FORGE YELLS]

20:12.336 --> 20:14.420
Geordi, are you all right?

20:14.630 --> 20:16.547
Destroy the probe, sir. Quickly!

20:18.342 --> 20:20.176
Worf, target phasers.

20:22.679 --> 20:24.972
- Phasers locked on target.
- Fire!

20:31.688 --> 20:33.814
Welcome to the Bridge,
Mr. La Forge.

20:34.358 --> 20:35.816
Thank you, sir.

20:36.026 --> 20:37.568
lf that thing had managed
to scan us,

20:37.778 --> 20:40.780
we never would have had any chance
of saving the Enterprise.

20:45.911 --> 20:49.538
That probe was a transmitter
sending an alien computer program.

20:49.748 --> 20:52.166
The same program
that is currently aboard the Enterprise

20:52.376 --> 20:54.752
trying to rewrite our software
in its own image.

20:54.962 --> 20:57.922
We have two completely incompatible
computer systems

20:58.131 --> 20:59.674
trying to interact.

20:59.883 --> 21:01.884
That's why the instruments
have become so erratic?

21:02.094 --> 21:03.469
- Yes.
- What can you do?

21:03.679 --> 21:04.720
Not very much.

21:04.930 --> 21:07.014
The lconian program
is so sophisticated,

21:07.224 --> 21:08.683
l may never understand it.

21:08.892 --> 21:10.142
Consider, captain,

21:10.352 --> 21:13.854
this program has entered
an alien database. Ours.

21:14.064 --> 21:15.481
And in less than seven hours

21:15.691 --> 21:17.525
has managed
to not only learn our systems,

21:17.734 --> 21:19.944
but has begun
to reprogram our computer.

21:20.153 --> 21:22.238
And so the earlier probe
was responsible

21:22.447 --> 21:24.156
for the Yamato's destruction?

21:24.366 --> 21:26.450
Yes. But only inasmuch
as it was the probe

21:26.660 --> 21:28.744
that transmitted the program.

21:28.954 --> 21:30.705
But we weren't scanned
by that probe.

21:30.914 --> 21:32.748
How did this thing
get aboard the Enterprise?

21:32.958 --> 21:34.792
DATA:
We downloaded the Yamato log,

21:35.002 --> 21:37.003
and contained in the log
was the program.

21:37.713 --> 21:40.131
Why didn't we suffer the same fate?

21:40.340 --> 21:43.217
Well, the program affected all of the
Yamato's systems simultaneously.

21:43.427 --> 21:46.804
But with us, it was deposited within
a specific section of our mainframe.

21:47.014 --> 21:49.557
So it's having to work its way out
from that location.

21:49.766 --> 21:51.892
That gives us
a little breathing space.

21:52.102 --> 21:54.186
Not much.

21:56.481 --> 21:59.275
The injury reports
are increasing too, sir.

21:59.776 --> 22:02.445
Dr. Pulaski is unwilling
to trust the turbolifts.

22:02.654 --> 22:05.740
She is sending medical teams
through the access tunnels.

22:06.908 --> 22:10.453
Captain, the Enterprise computer
system is a lot like our own bodies,

22:10.662 --> 22:13.164
with voluntary
and involuntary systems.

22:13.373 --> 22:14.457
And probably 90 percent

22:14.666 --> 22:16.792
of what goes on in this ship
is done automatically.

22:17.002 --> 22:19.045
Completely out of our control.

22:19.755 --> 22:22.506
We're sitting on a bomb
that could go off any second,

22:22.716 --> 22:24.175
or maybe never.

22:34.728 --> 22:36.687
The biobeds aren't working.

22:36.897 --> 22:39.273
The ship is falling apart.

22:39.483 --> 22:43.110
l've had 35 emergency calls
scattered across 1 2 decks.

22:43.320 --> 22:47.281
My trauma teams are being run ragged
trying to respond.

22:47.783 --> 22:48.949
Biobeds.

22:49.159 --> 22:50.993
- Dr. Pulaski.
- Yes?

22:51.203 --> 22:53.412
l've got a problem here.

22:53.622 --> 22:57.375
- The knitter isn't working.
- Uh, try a splint.

22:57.584 --> 23:00.419
- Doctor?
- Splint. lt's a very ancient concept.

23:00.629 --> 23:04.090
You take two flat pieces of wood
or plastic, a bandage.

23:04.299 --> 23:05.633
The broken limb is kept immobile.

23:05.842 --> 23:08.219
That's crazy.
That's not practicing medicine.

23:08.428 --> 23:11.055
Oh, yes, it is. lt's a time-honored way
to practice medicine,

23:11.264 --> 23:15.976
with your head and your heart
and your hands. So jump to it.

23:18.563 --> 23:20.106
Damn.

23:20.315 --> 23:22.775
Try a bypass
on the shield control interface.

23:22.984 --> 23:24.235
Oh, no go.

23:24.444 --> 23:27.571
Let me see if l can directly access
the master program.

23:27.739 --> 23:29.573
[GRUNTS]

23:34.830 --> 23:36.372
- Data?
- Yes?

23:36.581 --> 23:37.748
What happened?

23:37.958 --> 23:40.209
Any answer
would be mere speculation.

23:40.419 --> 23:44.213
This is yet another example of how
our actions have random results.

23:44.423 --> 23:47.091
Thanks, Data. l noticed.

23:47.884 --> 23:50.928
Life support has failed
on Decks 7 and 1 3, sir.

23:51.138 --> 23:54.014
Now, what if this thing manages
to rewrite our entire system?

23:54.224 --> 23:56.767
lt's so far beyond us we have no hope
of ever understanding it,

23:56.977 --> 23:58.644
let alone controlling it.

23:58.979 --> 24:01.313
Our own ignorance could kill us.

24:01.523 --> 24:03.399
PlCARD:
We may neve--

24:03.942 --> 24:05.401
We may never reach that point.

24:05.610 --> 24:09.071
A variation of what happened
to the Yamato might destroy us first.

24:09.281 --> 24:12.324
So we just sit here and watch our ship
disintegrate around us?

24:12.951 --> 24:15.786
The probe was launched
from lconia.

24:16.079 --> 24:19.415
Probably
from an automated system.

24:21.543 --> 24:24.628
There may be records
near the launch site

24:24.838 --> 24:27.089
that could help us find a solution.

24:29.217 --> 24:30.676
l'll arrange an away team.

24:30.886 --> 24:32.553
And l'll lead it.

24:33.096 --> 24:35.514
- You will lead it?
- Yes.

24:35.724 --> 24:38.350
Sir, we've had this conversation
a hundred times.

24:38.560 --> 24:39.727
And we will have it again.

24:39.936 --> 24:41.937
l've been studying the lconians
since l was a cadet.

24:42.147 --> 24:44.398
l have to be the one to go.

24:44.608 --> 24:46.775
The Enterprise is yours.

24:48.111 --> 24:50.029
For as long as she lasts.

24:56.244 --> 24:58.037
O'BRlEN:
l've got a lock on the energy source.

24:58.205 --> 24:59.663
For the moment, this baby's working.

24:59.873 --> 25:02.958
- But that could change in an instant.
PlCARD: We're aware of the risks.

25:03.168 --> 25:04.960
Energize.

25:14.054 --> 25:15.846
Transport complete.

25:16.389 --> 25:17.765
Stay sharp, Mr. O'Brien.

25:17.933 --> 25:20.059
l wanna be able to pull them out
at a moment's notice.

25:20.227 --> 25:21.268
O'BRlEN:
Aye, sir.

25:21.436 --> 25:22.520
[PANEL BEEPlNG]

25:22.687 --> 25:24.271
Commander, Romulan vessel.

25:25.607 --> 25:27.024
RlKER:
Open hailing frequencies.

25:27.234 --> 25:29.026
They're arming photon torpedoes.

25:29.236 --> 25:30.986
Shields up. Go to red alert.

25:31.780 --> 25:33.322
Sir, the shields aren't responding.

25:33.782 --> 25:35.824
They're preparing
to fire photon torpedoes.

25:36.034 --> 25:38.244
Mr. Crusher, l need those shields!

25:38.578 --> 25:39.912
l'm trying, sir.

25:40.121 --> 25:41.205
They're firing.

25:51.841 --> 25:53.425
What happened?

25:54.010 --> 25:57.137
lnstead of firing,
they suddenly disarmed and canceled.

25:58.139 --> 25:59.682
Fate...

26:01.142 --> 26:05.980
protects fools, little children,
and ships named Enterprise.

26:08.984 --> 26:11.860
Lock phasers on the Romulans
and hold your fire.

26:12.362 --> 26:14.572
Sir, the shields are back up.

26:15.073 --> 26:16.991
lmpeccable timing.

26:17.284 --> 26:18.742
Sir, the shields are back down.

26:18.952 --> 26:20.786
Phaser banks are down.

26:20.996 --> 26:22.246
Shields are back up.

26:23.123 --> 26:25.833
ln another time and place,
this could be funny.

26:26.042 --> 26:28.085
Status of torpedo banks?

26:28.420 --> 26:29.461
They're down too.

26:29.671 --> 26:31.422
lf it should become necessary
to fight,

26:31.631 --> 26:34.550
could you arrange to find me
some rocks to throw at them?

26:36.052 --> 26:40.389
Sir, the Romulan torpedoes
are continuing to arm and disarm.

26:40.599 --> 26:42.891
Perhaps its attempt to fire
was unintentional.

26:43.101 --> 26:44.518
Open hailing frequencies.

26:44.728 --> 26:46.395
Open.

26:47.314 --> 26:49.607
Romulan vessel,
this is Commander William Riker,

26:49.816 --> 26:51.900
first officer of the U.S.S. Enterprise.

26:52.110 --> 26:54.778
Why did you attempt to fire on us?

26:54.988 --> 26:57.740
This is Subcommander Taris
ofthe Haakona.

26:57.949 --> 27:00.909
Why have you penetrated deeper
into the Neutral Zone?

27:01.119 --> 27:02.995
Why are you still here?

27:03.371 --> 27:06.248
l have claimed this planet
for the Romulan Empire.

27:06.458 --> 27:10.127
This is the Neutral Zone.
No one can claim anything.

27:10.337 --> 27:11.795
You will withdraw,

27:12.005 --> 27:16.175
or l will be forced to destroy your ship
and your away team.

27:21.931 --> 27:23.891
What the hell?

27:24.934 --> 27:28.479
This is your final warning. l will not--

27:29.814 --> 27:32.149
RlKER: Having a little trouble
with your systems, commander?

27:32.484 --> 27:35.861
Maybe we should consider
postponing the war

27:36.321 --> 27:39.406
until we solve
our more immediate problem.

27:39.991 --> 27:41.700
You're stalling for time.

27:41.910 --> 27:43.535
Sir, another probe launch
from the planet,

27:43.745 --> 27:45.162
heading toward the Romulans.

27:45.372 --> 27:47.915
- Have we got our phasers back?
- No, sir.

27:48.124 --> 27:51.877
Taris, if you have phaser capability,
prepare to use them now.

27:52.087 --> 27:54.880
- What?
- Destroy that probe!

28:07.394 --> 28:09.436
And not even a thank you.

28:09.646 --> 28:12.022
Subcommander Taris
is deeply frustrated,

28:12.232 --> 28:14.900
probably because her ship
is as crippled as the Enterprise.

28:15.110 --> 28:17.528
Why would the Romulans
be experiencing problems?

28:17.737 --> 28:18.987
They weren't probed.

28:19.197 --> 28:21.115
They must have tapped
into the Yamato log.

28:21.324 --> 28:22.908
[SYSTEMS POWER DOWN]

28:24.494 --> 28:27.162
Taris got a whole lot more
than she bargained for.

28:28.373 --> 28:29.832
Maintain red alert.

28:30.041 --> 28:34.753
Try to keep those shields up in case
Taris decides to act on her threat.

28:34.963 --> 28:36.505
WESLEY:
Commander?

28:36.715 --> 28:38.298
What about the away team?

28:38.508 --> 28:40.843
With the shields up,
we can't beam them back.

28:49.561 --> 28:50.936
PlCARD:
Captain's log, supplemental.

28:51.146 --> 28:53.814
While there is little left
on the surface of lconia,

28:54.023 --> 28:56.525
we have found what appears to be
a control center

28:56.735 --> 28:59.528
which seems
to have remained intact.

29:02.449 --> 29:04.533
WORF:
Come in, Enterprise.

29:06.119 --> 29:07.703
Still no response, sir.

29:07.912 --> 29:08.954
Keep trying them.

29:09.164 --> 29:11.665
Communications are bound
to be erratic.

29:13.209 --> 29:17.546
l would not like to become
a permanent resident of this planet.

29:17.964 --> 29:20.299
Nor would l, Mr. Worf.

29:25.263 --> 29:28.599
Scanners show no other life forms
on the planet, sir.

29:28.808 --> 29:31.059
PlCARD:
l would not expect any.

29:31.686 --> 29:34.563
Judging from the severity
of the bombardment,

29:34.773 --> 29:37.357
l doubt any lconians survived.

29:37.567 --> 29:39.318
Well...

29:40.278 --> 29:43.322
Mr. Data, let's see
what sense we can make of this.

29:43.531 --> 29:45.157
Aye, sir.

29:45.366 --> 29:48.160
This is very reminiscent of Dinasian.

29:48.369 --> 29:49.411
Yes, sir.

29:49.871 --> 29:53.540
There are also similarities
to Dewan and lccobar.

29:53.750 --> 29:56.335
ls it possible they could be branches
of the same language family,

29:56.544 --> 29:59.379
- beginning with lconian?
- lt is, sir.

30:00.673 --> 30:03.050
Run a comparison
using basic simple words

30:03.259 --> 30:05.594
from Dinasian, Dewan, and lccobar.

30:05.804 --> 30:09.014
See if we can reconstruct
a common root language.

30:09.224 --> 30:11.141
Accessing, sir.

30:22.737 --> 30:24.321
You're jumpy.

30:25.949 --> 30:28.784
The tension on the ship is very high.

30:32.372 --> 30:34.039
What's your recommendation?

30:35.959 --> 30:37.584
Give everyone something to do.

30:37.794 --> 30:39.795
Somewhere to focus their attention.

30:40.839 --> 30:42.589
All right.

30:44.968 --> 30:47.177
Let's consider evacuation.

30:47.512 --> 30:49.054
To the planet?

30:49.264 --> 30:53.183
l know it's probably impossible
with Taris sitting out there.

30:53.685 --> 30:56.603
But it would give everyone
something to do.

30:56.980 --> 30:58.438
You go and organize it.

30:58.648 --> 31:01.817
But you might need me if you have
to negotiate with Taris again.

31:02.193 --> 31:04.027
l'll manage.

31:04.362 --> 31:06.488
Right now they're more important.

31:18.793 --> 31:20.335
DATA:
Captain.

31:21.462 --> 31:24.506
Your original hypothesis is correct.

31:24.716 --> 31:27.050
lconian is the parent tongue
of a language family

31:27.260 --> 31:30.470
which consists of lccobar,
Dewan, and Dinasian.

31:30.680 --> 31:32.681
l've constructed
a basic working understanding

31:32.891 --> 31:34.850
through a comparison
of common root words

31:35.059 --> 31:37.019
such as mother, father, child,

31:37.228 --> 31:40.147
home, tribe, food, life,
death, yours, ours, mine.

31:40.356 --> 31:42.065
Data, Data, Data.

31:42.275 --> 31:44.067
You do understand, sir,
that my interpretation

31:44.277 --> 31:46.069
of the symbols will not be exact.

31:46.279 --> 31:48.822
Yes. Let's get on with it.

31:49.282 --> 31:51.658
This would appear to be
manual override.

32:03.504 --> 32:06.757
That was not manual override.

32:07.634 --> 32:10.677
Demons of air and darkness,
indeed.

32:14.682 --> 32:17.392
- What is that?
- A gateway.

32:17.602 --> 32:21.188
These scenes
could be holographic images.

32:21.397 --> 32:22.439
PlCARD:
Be careful.

32:25.818 --> 32:27.277
Data!

32:27.612 --> 32:28.987
That was very foolish.

32:29.197 --> 32:31.448
But we have established
that this is not a holograph.

32:31.658 --> 32:33.158
lf l step through and investigate,

32:33.368 --> 32:36.370
we could determine
whether this is truly a gateway.

32:36.579 --> 32:40.999
No, Data. You might not be able
to get back, and l can't risk losing you.

32:41.209 --> 32:42.501
lf it is not illusion,

32:42.710 --> 32:45.921
this gate would seem to take us
beyond the confines of this planet.

32:46.130 --> 32:48.590
ls this how the lconians traveled?

32:49.175 --> 32:52.719
Crossing light years
as easily as we would cross a room?

32:53.054 --> 32:56.515
Those places could be on worlds
in distant corners of the galaxy.

32:56.724 --> 33:00.936
l think the lconians
might have outfoxed their enemies.

33:01.896 --> 33:04.481
Maybe they didn't all die
in the bombardment.

33:04.691 --> 33:07.818
Some of them could have passed
through this.

33:08.486 --> 33:10.570
This is what Varley feared.

33:10.780 --> 33:13.615
- This is what he died for.
- Sir?

33:14.117 --> 33:17.619
The Romulans could use
this technology as a weapon.

33:17.829 --> 33:21.581
- Like the lconians did.
- No, l disagree.

33:21.791 --> 33:23.667
Captain,
there is nothing in this room

33:23.876 --> 33:26.837
to indicate it was used
as a military command center.

33:27.046 --> 33:29.631
Perhaps a transporter room.

33:30.800 --> 33:32.384
But the probe was hostile.

33:32.552 --> 33:34.302
PlCARD:
We can't make that assumption.

33:34.512 --> 33:36.096
The effect on the Yamato
was devastating.

33:36.305 --> 33:39.433
But what if it was by accident,
not by design?

33:39.726 --> 33:42.811
What l'm going to say
may sound unscientific,

33:43.021 --> 33:46.815
but standing on this soil,
breathing in this air,

33:47.025 --> 33:49.693
my instincts tell me
that we may have got them wrong.

33:49.902 --> 33:52.404
But we do know
the lconians were conquerors.

33:52.613 --> 33:54.322
PlCARD: But that knowledge
was passed down

33:54.532 --> 33:56.575
by the descendants of those
who attacked this world.

33:56.784 --> 34:00.662
The victors invariably write the history
to their own advantage.

34:00.872 --> 34:03.790
There is an unfortunate tendency
in many cultures

34:04.000 --> 34:06.960
to fear what they do not understand.

34:07.170 --> 34:11.214
lt's possible that their enemies,
confronted by this technology,

34:11.424 --> 34:14.342
were driven to attack the lconians
out of fear.

34:16.679 --> 34:18.263
Sir!

34:24.854 --> 34:26.605
Was that really the Enterprise?

34:27.398 --> 34:29.483
l believe that it was.

34:30.318 --> 34:32.819
Gentlemen, we have a way home.

34:33.029 --> 34:36.615
Captain, there is a vast
underground power source

34:36.824 --> 34:39.409
which is controlled by this console.

34:39.702 --> 34:41.745
l believe my triggering
of the gateway

34:41.954 --> 34:44.623
has caused a dramatic upsurge
in the power level.

34:46.292 --> 34:49.586
Ah. l have access.

35:08.356 --> 35:10.440
PlCARD:
Data, can you hear me?

35:11.192 --> 35:13.193
Data, respond.

35:13.569 --> 35:16.279
- Captain.
- Are you all right?

35:16.489 --> 35:20.117
No. l am damaged.

35:20.326 --> 35:21.785
How bad is it?

35:22.328 --> 35:26.289
The lconian program is attempting
to rewrite my software.

35:26.499 --> 35:28.291
Physical manifestations,

35:28.668 --> 35:31.503
blindness. Motor con--

35:32.296 --> 35:36.883
Sir, without him we have no hope
of deciphering the program.

35:38.469 --> 35:41.471
Captain, the Enterprise again.

35:45.643 --> 35:47.269
How long is the interval?

35:47.478 --> 35:50.689
About four minutes,
if the cycle holds.

35:50.898 --> 35:52.649
The next time
the Enterprise appears,

35:52.859 --> 35:54.067
go through it with Data.

35:54.277 --> 35:56.778
Geordi will be able to learn from him.
Maybe help him.

35:56.988 --> 36:00.991
Sir, we have not yet established that
that is truly a gateway.

36:01.200 --> 36:02.659
This will be the test.

36:03.244 --> 36:04.786
Aye, sir.

36:07.623 --> 36:08.748
Destroy the tricorder.

36:10.585 --> 36:13.503
Sir, it contains everything
we discovered up to this point.

36:13.713 --> 36:16.798
And that is precisely
why it must be destroyed.

36:18.134 --> 36:19.801
How long?

36:20.720 --> 36:22.053
About three minutes.

36:23.639 --> 36:26.016
l'm running out of time.

36:26.642 --> 36:28.185
We all are.

36:28.394 --> 36:29.769
Data?

36:30.354 --> 36:33.648
Data, l have to destroy this.

36:33.858 --> 36:35.609
This control room and its technology

36:35.818 --> 36:37.652
must not be allowed to fall
into Romulan hands.

36:37.862 --> 36:40.071
DATA:
l understand, sir.

36:40.281 --> 36:41.323
How?

36:41.532 --> 36:43.658
How do l do it?
How do l destroy everything?

36:43.868 --> 36:46.411
The control room, the probes,
all of it.

36:48.998 --> 36:52.459
The power source, sir.

36:53.294 --> 36:55.170
l detonate it.

36:55.671 --> 36:57.214
But how? How do l do that?

36:57.423 --> 37:00.050
The probes, sir.

37:00.259 --> 37:03.386
Probes? The probes.

37:04.597 --> 37:06.264
Launch.

37:06.474 --> 37:08.600
l launch the probes?

37:08.809 --> 37:11.019
But why?

37:11.687 --> 37:13.104
What good will that do?

37:13.314 --> 37:16.858
- The doors, sir.
- Doors?

37:17.235 --> 37:19.361
Perhaps the probes
are in a launch bay.

37:20.780 --> 37:24.032
lf the doors are closed,
then the backwash from the rockets

37:24.200 --> 37:26.576
will spill into the power bridge
and there'll be an overload.

37:26.744 --> 37:27.786
Yes, sir.

37:27.954 --> 37:30.747
But the doors will open automatically
when the launch begins.

37:31.457 --> 37:34.709
- And l will override.
- Correct, sir.

37:36.379 --> 37:38.922
Which control keys? Damn.

37:39.215 --> 37:40.799
Of course, you can't see.

37:41.008 --> 37:42.717
Help.

37:44.720 --> 37:45.971
Worf, help him up.

37:51.310 --> 37:53.186
Describe, please.

37:53.396 --> 37:55.397
l'm standing directly
in front of the gate.

37:55.606 --> 37:58.275
